  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing comprehensive AML programs\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n- Training staff on detection and prevention\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implementing enhanced monitoring for potential risks\n- Developing risk-based compliance strategies\n\n5. Legal Penalties\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminals from using financial systems to launder money and finance illegal activities. Regulatory agencies like FinCEN in the United States enforce these requirements through strict oversight and significant penalties for non-compliance.",
